83rd OREGON LEGISLATIVE ASSEMBLY--2026 Regular Session
A-Engrossed
House Bill 4028
Ordered by the House February 16
Including House Amendments dated February 16
Sponsored by Representatives HARBICK, NOSSE; Representatives BOICE, BUNCH, MARSH, OWENS, PHAM H,
RIEKE SMITH, SKARLATOS, WALTERS, Senator SMITH DB (Presession filed.)
SUMMARY
The following summary is not prepared by the sponsors of the measure and is not a part of the body thereof subject
to consideration by the Legislative Assembly. It is an editor’s brief statement of the essential features of the
measure. The statement includes a measure digest written in compliance with applicable readability standards.
Digest: The Act limits how insurers, OHA and CCOs may conduct audits. The Act adds
new information that some carriers must report to DCBS. (Flesch Readability Score: 62.7).
[Digest: The Act limits how insurers, OHA and CCOs may conduct audits. The Act adds new in-
formation that some carriers must report to DCBS. The Act takes effect 91 days after session ends.
(Flesch Readability Score: 66.4).]
Imposes requirements and restrictions on insurer and coordinated care organization audits of
claims for reimbursement submitted by behavioral health treatment providers. Becomes operative
on January 1, 2027.
Adds information that certain carriers must annually report to the Department of Consumer and
Business Services regarding compliance with behavioral health parity requirements.
[Takes effect on the 91st day following adjournment sine die.]
1 A BILL FOR AN ACT
2 Relating to behavioral health; creating new provisions; and amending ORS 743B.427.
3 Be It Enacted by the People of the State of Oregon:
4 SECTION 1. Section 2 of this 2026 Act is added to and made a part of the Insurance Code.
5 SECTION 2. (1) As used in this section:
6 (a) “Audit” means an on-site or remote review of records of or claims made by a provider
7 by or on behalf of an insurer.
8 (b)(A) “Behavioral health treatment” includes:
9 (i) Mental health treatment and services as defined in ORS 743B.427; and
10 (ii) Substance use disorder treatment and services as defined in ORS 743B.427.
11 (B) “Behavioral health treatment” does not include treatment or services provided in:
12 (i) A hospital;
13 (ii) A hospital-affiliated clinic, as defined in ORS 442.612; or
14 (iii) A group medical practice that includes outpatient mental health or substance use
15 disorder treatment.
16 (c) “Claim” means a request made by a provider to an insurer to reimburse the cost of
17 behavioral health treatment provided to a beneficiary of a policy or certificate of health in-
18 surance offered by the insurer.
19 (d) “Clerical error” means a minor error in the keeping, recording or transcribing of re-
20 cords or documents or in the handling of electronic or hard copies of correspondence.
21 (e) “Fraud” means an intentional misrepresentation made by an individual with the
22 knowledge that the misrepresentation could result in an unauthorized benefit to the indi-
NOTE: Matter in boldfaced type in an amended section is new; matter [italic and bracketed] is existing law to be omitted.
New sections are in boldfaced type.
LC 48

A-Eng. HB 4028
1 vidual or to another person.
2 (f) “Provider” means a person who is licensed, certified or otherwise authorized to pro-
3 vide behavioral health treatment in this state.
4 (2) An insurer that offers a policy or certificate of health insurance that reimburses the
5 cost of behavioral health treatment shall make available to all providers who submit claims
6 a separate document containing a detailed written description of all requirements for the
7 successful resolution of a claim that may be audited by the insurer in the future and the
8 requirements that applied in any previous period during which a claim of the provider was
9 audited. The description must:
10 (a) Be written in plain language that is easy to understand and that does not rely on
11 references to other sources such as statutes or contract provisions;
12 (b) Provide examples of documentation requirements for the submission of claims;
13 (c) Identify which requirements may result in recoupment for failure to comply;
14 (d) Explain which requirements apply to in-network providers and which apply to out-of-
15 network providers; and
16 (e) If the requirements differentiate between types of providers, explain the requirements
17 applicable to each type of provider.
18 (3) An insurer may not recoup from a provider a payment on a claim if the insurer has
19 failed to comply with subsection (2) of this section.
20 (4) An insurer shall notify providers no later than 30 days before the effective date of any
21 changes made by the insurer to the requirements described in subsection (2) of this section.
22 An insurer may not demand recoupment of a payment made on a claim based on new re-
23 quirements if the insurer has failed to comply with this subsection.
24 (5) An insurer’s audit of a claim:
25 (a) May not be conducted on any paid claim submitted by a provider on a date more than
26 12 months earlier or, in the case of suspected fraud, may not be conducted more than six
27 years after the date payment was made on the claim;
28 (b) For an audit initiated after payment is made on a claim, must be completed no later
29 than 180 days from the date the audit is initiated on the claim, unless a provider fails to
30 submit records in a timely fashion or initiates an appeal of the insurer’s audit finding;
31 (c) Must be reviewed by a behavioral health professional; and
32 (d) May not result in reversing or overturning a determination that a service is medically
33 necessary that was made by the insurer when the claim was submitted or prior authorization
34 of the service approved, unless the patient was no longer insured at the time the service was
35 provided.
36 (6) If an insurer uses sampling or similar methods to determine whether to initiate an
37 audit of a provider’s claims, the insurer:
38 (a) May initiate an audit only if the insurer identifies a high probability of an error; and
39 (b) May recoup from a provider only payments on individual claims for which the insurer
40 specifically identifies an error.
41 (7) In the course of an audit initiated prior to payment on a claim, an insurer shall re-
42 spond to a provider with findings no later than 30 days after the date the provider responds
43 to the insurer’s request for additional information regarding the claim.
44 (8) An insurer may not demand recoupment of a payment made on a claim based on a
45 clerical error.
[2]

A-Eng. HB 4028
1 (9) If an insurer identifies an error during an audit of a claim that results in the
2 insurer’s demand for recoupment of the insurer’s payment on the claim, the insurer:
3 (a) Shall provide a detailed description of the error and allow a provider a reasonable
4 opportunity of not less than 30 days to rectify the error; and
5 (b) Shall allow the provider to use a repayment plan of up to three years to repay the
6 claim unless the recoupment is based on an insurer’s duplicate payment on a claim.
7 (10) An insurer may not begin a new audit of any claim submitted by a provider while
8 another audit is in process. A subsequent audit may not be initiated until the provider has
9 been given the opportunity to correct mistakes identified in the previous audit and complete
10 any corrective action plan resulting from the previous audit.
11 (11) An insurer conducting an audit may not structure compensation paid to an employee
12 or agent conducting an audit in any manner that creates a direct financial incentive to the
13 employee or agent to identify errors that result in recoupment.
14 (12) An insurer may not charge a provider for the costs of conducting an audit.
15 (13) The provisions of this section apply to audits conducted by an insurer and to audits
16 conducted by a third party on behalf of an insurer.
17 (14) In the event of an audit dispute between a provider and an insurer, the insurer:
18 (a) Shall continue to cover medically necessary services for the patient during the dis-
19 pute, unless the insurer finds clear evidence of fraud or immediate patient safety concerns.
20 (b) May not hold the patient financially responsible for services deemed medically neces-
21 sary at the time of delivery, even if the provider is later subject to recoupment.
22 SECTION 3. Section 4 of this 2026 Act is added to and made a part of ORS chapter 414.
23 SECTION 4. (1) As used in this section:
24 (a) “Audit” means an on-site or remote review of records of or claims made by a provider
25 by or on behalf of a coordinated care organization or the Oregon Health Authority.
26 (b)(A) “Behavioral health treatment” includes:
27 (i) Mental health treatment and services as defined in ORS 743B.427; and
28 (ii) Substance use disorder treatment and services as defined in ORS 743B.427.
29 (B) “Behavioral health treatment” does not include treatment or services provided in:
30 (i) A hospital;
31 (ii) A hospital-affiliated clinic, as defined in ORS 442.612; or
32 (iii) A group medical practice that includes outpatient mental health or substance use
33 disorder treatment.
34 (c) “Claim” means a request made by a provider to a coordinated care organization or
35 the authority to reimburse the cost of behavioral health treatment provided to a member
36 of the coordinated care organization or to a medical assistance recipient who is not enrolled
37 in a coordinated care organization.
38 (d) “Clerical error” means a minor error in the keeping, recording or transcribing of re-
39 cords or documents or in the handling of electronic or hard copies of correspondence.
40 (e) “Fraud” means an intentional misrepresentation made by an individual with the
41 knowledge that the misrepresentation could result in an unauthorized benefit to the indi-
42 vidual or to another person.
43 (f) “Provider” means an individual who is licensed, certified or otherwise authorized to
44 provide behavioral health treatment in this state.
45 (2) A coordinated care organization and the Oregon Health Authority shall make avail-
[3]

A-Eng. HB 4028
1 able to all providers all of the following regarding the requirements for the submission of
2 claims:
3 (a) Examples of documentation requirements for the submission of claims;
4 (b) Identification of which requirements may result in recoupment for failure to comply;
5 (c) An explanation of which requirements apply to in-network providers and which apply
6 to out-of-network providers; and
7 (d) If the requirements differentiate between types of providers, an explanation of the
8 requirements applicable to each type of provider.
9 (3) A coordinated care organization and the authority shall notify providers no later than
10 30 days before the effective date of any contract changes by the coordinated care organiza-
11 tion or changes by the authority to relevant administrative rules.
12 (4) An audit of a claim:
13 (a) May not be conducted on any paid claim submitted by a provider on a date more than
14 three years earlier without an indication of fraud or an improper payment;
15 (b) Except as provided in subsection (5) of this section, must be completed no later than
16 180 days from the date an audit is initiated on a claim;
17 (c) Must be conducted by a behavioral health professional; and
18 (d) May not result in reversing or overturning a determination that a service is medically
19 necessary made by a coordinated care organization or the authority when prior authorization
20 of the service was given.
21 (5) In the course of an audit, if a coordinated care organization or the authority requests
22 additional information regarding a claim, the coordinated care organization or the authority
23 shall respond to a provider with findings no later than 180 days after the date the audit was
24 initiated, unless an extension is agreed to in writing by all parties.
25 (6) If a coordinated care organization or the authority identifies an error during an audit
26 of a claim that results in a demand for recoupment of the payment on the claim:
27 (a) The coordinated care organization or the authority shall work with the provider on
28 a repayment plan, if requested.
29 (b) The provider may request, and is entitled to receive, a revised audit if the provider
30 has reason to believe that the coordinated care organization or the authority based the
31 finding of error on an incorrect provision of law.
32 (7) Unless required by federal law, a coordinated care organization or the authority con-
33 ducting an audit may not compensate an individual for conducting the audit in an amount
34 that is based on a percentage of the overpayments recouped or in any other way that creates
35 a financial incentive to identify errors that result in recoupment.
36 (8) The provisions of this section apply to audits conducted by a coordinated care organ-
37 ization and the authority and to audits conducted by a third party on behalf of a coordinated
38 care organization or the authority.
39 (9) In the event of an audit dispute between a provider and a coordinated care organiza-
40 tion or the authority, the coordinated care organization or the authority:
41 (a) Shall continue to cover medically necessary services for the patient during the dis-
42 pute, unless the coordinated care organization or the authority finds clear evidence of fraud
43 or immediate patient safety concerns.
44 (b) May not hold the patient financially responsible for services deemed medically neces-
45 sary at the time of delivery, even if the provider is later subject to recoupment.
